# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: view-transitions-api
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] Since October 2025, this feature works across the latest devices and browser versions.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] This feature might not work in older devices or browsers.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] The **`startViewTransition()`** method of the `Document` interface starts a new same-document (SPA), document-scoped view transition and returns a `ViewTransition` object to represent it.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] The sequence of steps followed when `startViewTransition()` is invoked is explained in the view transition process section.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] A callback function invoked to update the DOM during the SPA view transition process.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] The callback is invoked once the API has taken a snapshot of the current page.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] When the promise returned by the callback fulfills, the view transition begins in the next frame.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] If the promise returned by the callback rejects, the transition is abandoned.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] An object containing options to configure the view transition.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] The same `updateCallback` function described above.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] An array of strings representing the types applied to the view transition.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] View transition types enable selective application of CSS styles or JavaScript logic based on the type of transition occurring.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] See View transition API > Examples for a list of full examples.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] In this same-document view transition, we check if the browser supports view transitions.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] If there's no support, we set the background color using a fallback method which is applied immediately.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] Otherwise, we can safely call `document.startViewTransition()` with animation rules that we define in CSS.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] We are setting the `animation-duration` to 2 seconds using the `::view-transition-group` pseudo-element.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] If view transitions are supported, clicking the button will transition the color from one to another over 2 seconds.
[src:view-transitions-api/startviewtransition] Otherwise, the background color is set using a fallback method, without any animation.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] The **`view-transition-name`** CSS property specifies the view transition snapshot that selected elements will participate in.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] This enables you to animate those elements separately from the rest of the page, which uses the default cross-fade animation during a view transition.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] You can then define custom animation styles for these elements.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] An identifying name that causes the selected element to participate in a separate snapshot from the root snapshot.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] The `<custom-ident>` cannot be `auto`, `match-element`, `none`, or a CSS-wide keyword value.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] The browser automatically assigns a unique name to the selected element.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] This name is used to snapshot the element separately from all other elements on the page.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] The selected element will not participate in a separate snapshot, unless it has a parent element with a `view-transition-name` set, in which case it will be snapshotted as part of that element.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] By default, when a view transition is applied to a web app, all changes to the UI that occur during that transition are snapshotted and animated together.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] This is the default — or `root` — snapshot (see The view transition pseudo-element tree).
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] By default, this animation is a smooth cross-fade, which can be seen in action in the View Transitions SPA demo.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] You can then specify which animations you want for the before and after snapshots using the relevant view transition pseudo-elements — `::view-transition-old()` and `::view-transition-new()`.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] The `view-transition-name` `<custom-ident>` must be unique for each rendered element taking part in the view transition.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] If two rendered elements have the same `view-transition-name` at the same time, the `ViewTransition.ready` `Promise` will reject and the transition will be skipped.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] Sometimes you will want to animate multiple UI elements separately in a view transition.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] Because `match-element` assigns automatic `view-transition-name` values based on element identity, it can only be used for same-document view transitions.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] The auto-generated internal identifiers are not transferrable across different elements or documents.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] This example comes from the View Transitions SPA demo, which is a basic image gallery.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] The Basic SPA view transition provides a more detailed explanation of how this demo works.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] Most of the UI changes are animated using the `root` transition snapshot.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] We create a custom CSS animation and apply it to the `::view-transition-old(figure-caption)` and `::view-transition-new(figure-caption)` pseudo-elements.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] We also apply other styles to keep them both in the same place and to stop the default styling from interfering with our custom animations.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] This example contains a list of technologies–HTML, CSS, SVG, and JS–that are displayed in a sidebar next to a main content area, which starts out empty.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] Clicking a technology's heading animates its content into the adjoining content area that shows more details.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] The `<main>` element contains an unordered list and an `<article>` element.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] The multiple child `<li>` elements inside the list each contain an `<a>` element inside a heading.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] We use flexbox to lay out the `<li>` and the `<article>` side by side, and to make the list items share equal amount of space in the first column.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] The list takes up 35% of the container's width, while the `<article>` fills the remaining available horizontal space.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] We also define a rule that selects elements with the `active-item` class.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] When this class is applied to an element, the rule causes it to be positioned exactly over the top of the `<article>` element.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] This class will be applied to the list items via JavaScript when their links are clicked, which will initiate a view transition.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] By default, all elements in a view transition are animated together in a single cross-fade.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] In this example, however, we don't want this — we want each list item to have its own movement animation.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] The `match-element-applied` class is applied to the `<main>` element by default, which is why the checkbox in the Result frame is initially selected.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] If you uncheck it, the class is removed and the default cross-fade animation comes into effect instead.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] You can toggle the checkbox to compare the default animation with the one applied when `view-transition-name: match-element` is used.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] Next, we customize the animation by using the `::view-transition-group()` pseudo-element to apply an `animation-duration` to all the view transition groups (signified by the `*` identifier) and give all the old and new snapshots a `height` of `100%`.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] Running the `updateActiveItem()` function via the `startViewTransition()` function animates the display of technology details smoothly.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] Click a technology heading in the sidebar and notice the animation effect of its content into the main content area.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] There is also a checkbox, which is selected by default, so `view-transition-name: match-element` is applied.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition-name] Uncheck the checkbox and click a heading again to see how the view-transition works without `view-transition-name: match-element`.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition] The **`::view-transition`** CSS pseudo-element represents the root of the view transitions overlay, which contains all view transition snapshot groups and sits over the top of all other page content.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition] During a view transition, `::view-transition` is included in the associated pseudo-element tree as explained in The view transition pseudo-element tree.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition] It is the top-level node of this tree, and has one or more `::view-transition-group()`s as children.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transition] All `::view-transition-group()` pseudo-elements are positioned relative to the view transition root.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] The **View Transition API** provides a mechanism for easily creating animated transitions between different website and element views.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] This includes animating between DOM states in a single-page app (SPA), and animating the navigation between documents in a multi-page app (MPA).
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] View transitions are a popular design choice for reducing users' cognitive load, helping them stay in context, and reducing perceived loading latency as they move between states or views of an application.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] The View Transition API provides an easy way of handling the required view changes and transition animations for both the above use cases.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] Represents a `@view-transition` at-rule.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] Represents a view transition, and provides functionality to react to the transition reaching different states (e.g., ready to run the animation, or animation finished) or skip the transition altogether.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] A set-like object representing the types of an active view transition, which enables the types to be queried or modified on-the-fly during a transition.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] Starts a new same-document (SPA) view transition and returns a `ViewTransition` object to represent it.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] The event object for the `pagereveal` event.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] During a cross-document navigation, it allows you to manipulate the related view transition (providing access to the relevant `ViewTransition` object) from the document being navigated *to*, if a view transition was triggered by the navigation.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] The event object for the `pageswap` event.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] During a cross-document navigation, it allows you to manipulate the related view transition (providing access to the relevant `ViewTransition` object) from the document being navigated *from*, if a view transition was triggered by the navigation.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] It also provides access to information on the navigation type and current and destination document history entries.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] Fired when a document is first rendered, either when loading a fresh document from the network or activating a document (either from back/forward cache (bfcache) or prerender).
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] Fired when a document is about to be unloaded due to a navigation.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] Identifies the most critical content in the associated document for the user's initial view of the page.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] Document rendering will be blocked until the critical content has been parsed, ensuring a consistent first paint — and therefore, view transition — across all supporting browsers.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] In the case of a cross-document navigation, `@view-transition` is used to opt in the current and destination documents to undergo a view transition.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] Specifies the view transition snapshot that selected elements will participate in, which enables an element to be animated separately from the rest of the page during a view transition.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] Provides an additional method of styling selected elements that have a `view-transition-name`.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] Enables the discoverability of elements with `view-transition-name` values set on them (and therefore the creation of view transition snapshots) to be isolated to a specific element subtree.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] Matches elements when a view transition is in progress.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] Matches elements when a view transition with one or more specific types is in progress.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] The root of the view transitions overlay, which contains all view transitions and sits over the top of all other page content.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] The container for a view transition's old and new views — before and after the transition.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] A static snapshot of the old view, before the transition.
[src:view-transitions-api/view-transitions-api] A live representation of the new view, after the transition.
[src:view-transitions-api/viewtransition] The **`ViewTransition`** interface of the View Transition API represents an active view transition, and provides functionality to react to the transition reaching different states (e.g., ready to run the animation, or animation finished) or skip the transition altogether.
[src:view-transitions-api/viewtransition] When a view transition is triggered by a `startViewTransition()` call (or a page navigation in the case of MPA transitions), a sequence of steps is followed as explained in The view transition process.
[src:view-transitions-api/viewtransition] This also explains when the different promises fulfill.
[src:view-transitions-api/viewtransition] A `Promise` that fulfills once the transition animation is finished, and the new page view is visible and interactive to the user.
[src:view-transitions-api/viewtransition] A `Promise` that fulfills once the pseudo-element tree is created and the transition animation is about to start.
[src:view-transitions-api/viewtransition] A reference to the root `Element` of the view transition scope.
[src:view-transitions-api/viewtransition] A `ViewTransitionTypeSet` that allows the types set on the view transition to be accessed and modified.
[src:view-transitions-api/viewtransition] A `Promise` that fulfills when the promise returned by the `document.startViewTransition()` method's callback fulfills.
[src:view-transitions-api/viewtransition] Skips the animation part of the view transition, but doesn't skip running the `document.startViewTransition()` callback that updates the DOM.
[src:view-transitions-api/viewtransition] Delays finishing the view transition and the destruction of the associated pseudo-element tree until a `Promise` passed into the method has resolved.
[src:view-transitions-api/viewtransition] In the following SPA example, the `ViewTransition.ready` promise is used to trigger a custom circular reveal view transition emanating from the position of the user's cursor on click, with animation provided by the Web Animations API.
